Vexor is an independent reimplementation of the Solana validator in Zig — not
a fork of any existing client. Its runtime behavior is byte-for-byte
compatible with the Agave validator by design. That compatibility was achieved
by using the Apache-2.0 licensed projects below as REFERENCE IMPLEMENTATIONS
and DIFFERENTIAL TEST ORACLES — reading their source, reimplementing the
behavior in Zig, and verifying bit-for-bit against their output. The majority
of the tree is original Vexor work; where a subsystem was instead PORTED or
CARRIED from an upstream project, that lineage is declared below and
enumerated per-file/per-function in PROVENANCE.md. We do NOT claim "from
scratch, no reference" (see src/vex_crypto/NOTICE for the same principle
applied in detail to the crypto stack).

  • Agave — Anza  (anza-xyz/agave), Apache-2.0.
      Primary behavioral reference: consensus / fork choice, SVM + sBPF
      execution, compute-budget & cost model, CPI, vote / stake / loader
      programs, sysvars, account (LtHash) hashing. Vexor's implementations of
      these are reimplementations in Zig, verified byte-for-byte against
      Agave's output; no Agave (Rust) code is compiled into Vexor.

  • Firedancer — Jump Crypto  (firedancer-io/firedancer), Apache-2.0.
      Two distinct kinds of lineage:
      (a) Reference for leaf cryptography (the "Ballet" ed25519 / blake3 /
          bn254 / poseidon routines) and select high-performance data
          structures. Vexor no longer links any Firedancer C code — its
          cryptography is an independent pure-Zig reimplementation,
          unconditionally (the historical -Dpure_zig build flag is retained
          as a no-op for recipe compatibility).
      (b) Whole-file Zig PORTS of Firedancer C modules in the SVM core and
          networking stack — logic translated near-line-by-line from the
          upstream C into Zig (no C is compiled or linked). Each file
          declares its upstream source in its own header and in
          PROVENANCE.md; the principal ones:
            src/vex_svm/executor.zig           ← fd_executor.c
            src/vex_svm/runtime.zig            ← fd_runtime.c
            src/vex_svm/native/system_v2.zig   ← fd_system_program.c
            src/vex_svm/native/vote_v2.zig     ← fd_vote_program.c
            src/vex_svm/native/nonce.zig       ← fd_system_program_nonce.c
            src/vex_svm/native/stake_state.zig ← fd_stake_types.h/.c
            src/vex_svm/rewards.zig            ← fd_rewards.c/.h
            src/vex_svm/hashes.zig             ← fd_hashes.c
            src/vex_svm/tx_dispatcher.zig      ← fd_rdisp (single-lane)
            src/vex_svm/siphash13.zig          ← fd_siphash13.c (byte-exact)
            src/vex_network/bmtree.zig         ← fd_bmtree.h
          plus further declared ports (blockhash queue, stakes/stake-history
          math, FEC/Reed-Solomon resolver, gossip parse paths, tower
          push_vote, and others) — see PROVENANCE.md for the complete
          row-level list.

  • Sig — Syndica  (Syndica/sig), Apache-2.0.
      Three distinct kinds of lineage:
      (a) The zk-ElGamal proof subsystem (src/vex_bpf2/zksdk/) is an
          INDEPENDENT VEXOR RE-IMPLEMENTATION, written from scratch in native
          Zig across 12 modules (~8,200 lines):
            elgamal.zig, pedersen.zig, merlin.zig,
            range_proof/bulletproofs.zig, range_proof/ipp.zig,
            sigma_proofs/ciphertext_ciphertext.zig,
            sigma_proofs/ciphertext_commitment.zig,
            sigma_proofs/percentage_with_cap.zig,
            sigma_proofs/pubkey_validity.zig,
            sigma_proofs/zero_ciphertext.zig,
            sigma_proofs/grouped_ciphertext/2_handles.zig,
            sigma_proofs/grouped_ciphertext/3_handles.zig
          These files previously carried Sig's implementation substantially
          verbatim; they have since been fully rewritten as Vexor's own code.
          Sig's implementation was used as a reference and differential-test
          oracle throughout that rewrite — Vexor's re-implementation is
          verified byte-for-byte against it (per-module parity KATs plus
          3,124/3,124 zk_sdk conformance) — but it is not a copy of Sig's
          code and carries no Sig copyright. Credited here and in
          PROVENANCE.md (@prov:zksdk.module-map).
      (b) The legacy sBPF interpreter (src/vex_bpf/vm.zig +
          vm_interpreter.zig) was originally ported from Sig's
          src/vm/{interpreter,memory,sbpf,elf}.zig and has since been
          heavily reworked (PROVENANCE.md @prov:vm.module-map). The vex_bpf2
          rebuild that ships beside it is an independent spec-for-spec
          implementation against solana-sbpf.
      (c) The ed25519 vectorized field/point kernels under
          src/vex_crypto/ed25519/ are curve25519-dalek IFMA kernels carried
          substantially verbatim via Sig — fully documented in
          src/vex_crypto/NOTICE.
      Beyond these, Sig served as a reference for Zig-idiomatic Solana
      structures during early bring-up. One Sig-derived subsystem HAS been
      removed: the vote-program transplant used as a differential oracle
      while Vexor's own vote executor was validated. voteforge, the live
      vote executor, is Vexor-original and imports no Sig code.

Per-subsystem provenance — exactly which Vexor file/function reimplements,
ports, or byte-exact-matches which upstream source — is maintained in
PROVENANCE.md (the provenance ledger).

Vexor also vendors one piece of third-party code directly (not a behavioral
reference — actual linked source):

  • blst — Supranational LLC  (supranational/blst), Apache-2.0.
      BLS12-381 pairing-cryptography library, vendored at vendor/blst/ and
      built directly from its C/assembly source. See vendor/blst/LICENSE for
      the license text as distributed by Supranational.

Additional carried artifacts are declared in src/vex_crypto/NOTICE: the
fiat-crypto BN254 base-field Montgomery reduction (MIT/Apache-2.0/
BSD-1-Clause), the ARM optimized-routines pow port (Apache-2.0), the
light-poseidon / circomlib Poseidon parameters (reached via Firedancer), and
the Google Wycheproof KAT corpus (Apache-2.0).

